Date: Sat, 5 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: EU Anima health and welfare web-site, 4 Feb 2005 [edited]
<http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/animal/diseases/adns/index_en.htm>

Animal Disease Notification System (ADNS) Weekly report, 4 Feb 2005
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Table 11 : Animal Disease Situation per Country and per Disease, 1 Jan 2005
to 4 Feb 2005
In relation to Bluetongue, the said table contained the following data:
France confirmed 5 outbreaks during the said period (last date of
confirmation 1 Feb 2005).
Spain confirmed 6 outbreaks during the said period (last date of
confirmation 3 Jan 2005).
A map, showing the regions where outbreaks of bluetongue have been reported
by Spain and Portugal, is displayed at
<http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/animal/diseases/adns/map_adns.htm>
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Portugal has not reported any outbreaks during 2005; the last outbreak
there, according to Portugal's follow-up report No 4 to the OIE (14 Jan
2005), occurred in a sheep flock in Alentejo, starting 7 Dec 2004. Of 135
susceptible animals, 49 showed clinical signs, 22 died, and 113 were
destroyed. <http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_10.HTM#Sec9>
As recently summarized by Purce et al [1], since its arrival in Europe in
1998, BT has caused the deaths of more than one million sheep. The epidemic
began during October 1998, when BTV-9 was detected on 4 Greek islands close
to the Turkish coast (Rhodes, Leros, Kos and Samos). In subsequent years up
to 2004, BTV-9 spread northward (into western regions of Turkey, Bulgaria,
Kosovo, Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, the former Yugoslav Republic of
Macedonia, Serbia and Montenegro, and Croatia) and westward (into mainland
Greece, Italy, Sicily, Sardinia and Corsica). A further 3 serotypes, BTV-1,
BTV-4 and BTV-16, also entered Europe from the east (through Greece) and
then spread westwards. A separate incursion of BTV-2 also occurred in 2000,
spreading from Tunisia and/or Algeria into Sardinia, Sicily, mainland
Italy, Corsica and the Balearic islands. In late 2004, further incursions
(this time of BTV-4) occurred from Morocco into southwestern Spain and
southern Portugal. This last outbreak is expected to be terminated by now,
following the seasonal pattern, related to the annual fall in temperatures,
as observed in other BT-infected Middle-Eastern countries for decades.
The outbreaks involving Spain and Portugal were caused by BTV serotype 4.
Its recurrence next season (generally, commencing in July/August) cannot be
predicted at this stage. Some serotypes have now persisted for up to 6
years in parts of Europe, a pattern that is consistent with frequent
over-wintering as opposed to reincursion of particular strains.
Subscribers are referred to the following new publications dealing with BT
spread into and within Europe:
1. B.V. Purse et al. Climate change and the recent emergence of bluetongue
in Europe. Nature Reviews Microbiology 3, 2, 171-181 (2005).
2. Proceedings, OIE Third International Bluetongue Symposium. Vet. Ital.,
40 (3), (2005) (in print) - Mod.AS]
